WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.839 --> 00:00:03.630
JODY KENT LAVY: Hi.

00:00:03.630 --> 00:00:04.446
I'm Jody Kent Lavy.

00:00:04.446 --> 00:00:06.320
I'm the director of the
Campaign for the Fair

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:07.220
Sentencing of Youth.

00:00:07.220 --> 00:00:10.279
We are a nonprofit
based in Washington, DC.

00:00:10.279 --> 00:00:12.070
And we are working to
end the United States

00:00:12.070 --> 00:00:14.550
practice of sentencing our
children to life in prison

00:00:14.550 --> 00:00:16.610
without the
possibility of parole.

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:18.130
Many people ask us
what does it mean

00:00:18.130 --> 00:00:19.970
to sentence a kid
to life in prison

00:00:19.970 --> 00:00:21.620
without the
possibility of parole?

00:00:21.620 --> 00:00:23.286
Doesn't life in prison
mean that they'll

00:00:23.286 --> 00:00:25.345
get out after 15, 20, 25 years?

00:00:25.345 --> 00:00:27.370
And in fact, life
without parole means

00:00:27.370 --> 00:00:30.700
that these are children who've
been told that they'll never,

00:00:30.700 --> 00:00:32.520
ever see a second chance.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:34.870
They'll never have an
opportunity for review.

00:00:34.870 --> 00:00:38.110
And for context, Charles
Manson from the great state

00:00:38.110 --> 00:00:41.230
of California has come
up for review 12 times.

00:00:41.230 --> 00:00:43.380
But these kids never will.

00:00:43.380 --> 00:00:45.740
In the United States, there
are more than 2,500 people

00:00:45.740 --> 00:00:47.680
who've been sentenced
to life without parole.

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:50.460
And they are concentrated
in five states.

00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:52.210
The vast majority of
them are concentrated

00:00:52.210 --> 00:00:56.020
in just five states,
California being one of them.

00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:58.580
Everyone always guesses
Texas, but that's actually

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:00.120
not one of the top five states.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:03.030
Texas actually banned life
without parole for children.

00:01:03.030 --> 00:01:05.260
Michigan, Pennsylvania--
Pennsylvania

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:09.060
leads the nation in
this practice-- Florida,

00:01:09.060 --> 00:01:12.580
and-- did I get them all--
California, Pennsylvania,

00:01:12.580 --> 00:01:16.734
Louisiana, Michigan,
and Florida.

00:01:16.734 --> 00:01:17.410
Is that five?

00:01:17.410 --> 00:01:17.910
Yeah.

00:01:17.910 --> 00:01:20.220
OK.

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:24.392
So in the last few years since
our organization was launched,

00:01:24.392 --> 00:01:26.850
there's been a tremendous amount
of progress on this issue.

00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:30.170
In fact, in California,
just since 2012, there

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:31.586
have been a number
of reforms that

00:01:31.586 --> 00:01:34.860
has made it possible for these
young people who are serving

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:38.280
time in prisons across the
state to come up for review

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:40.620
and prove that they're
eligible or should be

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:43.630
eligible for a second chance.

00:01:43.630 --> 00:01:45.450
The US Supreme Court
has now stepped

00:01:45.450 --> 00:01:48.120
in several times to the limit
the practice of sentencing kids

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:49.490
to life without parole.

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:51.033
And in doing so,
they've relied a lot

00:01:51.033 --> 00:01:53.210
on adolescent development
research, which

00:01:53.210 --> 00:01:54.960
shows that kids
are fundamentally

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:57.350
different than adults
and that as a result

00:01:57.350 --> 00:02:00.560
of those unique characteristics
of children, things that all

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:02.970
of us know having been teens--
that they tend to be more

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:05.428
reckless the adults, that they
are more susceptible to peer

00:02:05.428 --> 00:02:08.639
pressure, that they don't
think through the consequences

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:12.550
of their actions the same way
adults do, and they're also

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:15.460
uniquely capable of change
and rehabilitation--

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:18.290
so relying on that science
and relying on that research,

00:02:18.290 --> 00:02:20.497
the Supreme Court has
stepped in to limit

00:02:20.497 --> 00:02:22.830
the practice of sentencing
youth to life without parole.

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:26.940
So what the campaign does is
we organize a national movement

00:02:26.940 --> 00:02:29.810
to take these Supreme
Court decisions

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:32.705
and to educate policymakers
around the country

00:02:32.705 --> 00:02:36.587
to help them recognize these
differences between kids

00:02:36.587 --> 00:02:38.170
and adults and to
make sure that we're

00:02:38.170 --> 00:02:40.920
holding our young people
accountable in age-appropriate

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:42.420
ways and that we're
never sentencing

00:02:42.420 --> 00:02:44.080
them to die in prison.

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:46.940
And a really critical
component of our work

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:49.340
has been just in
the last few years

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:54.640
to demonstrate through a lot
of different sort of techniques

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:56.950
involving public education,
legislative advocacy,

00:02:56.950 --> 00:02:59.624
and litigation just who
these young people are

00:02:59.624 --> 00:03:01.290
and what they're
capable of when they're

00:03:01.290 --> 00:03:03.060
given the right opportunities.

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:05.487
And so one of the
leaders in this work--

00:03:05.487 --> 00:03:07.070
probably the leader
in this work-- who

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:12.230
has been the face of
shifting this narrative

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:15.240
in a lot of venues
around the country

00:03:15.240 --> 00:03:17.490
is my colleague,
Xavier McElrath-Bey,

00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:19.570
who you're going to
hear from in a minute.

00:03:19.570 --> 00:03:22.900
I just want to say that
just in the last five years,

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:26.250
we have nearly doubled the
number of states that ban

00:03:26.250 --> 00:03:27.670
juvenile life without parole.

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:29.772
That said, the
majority of states

00:03:29.772 --> 00:03:31.730
still allow this sentence
for our young people.

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:32.850
We're the only
country in the world

00:03:32.850 --> 00:03:33.974
that does this to our kids.

00:03:33.974 --> 00:03:35.930
So we have a long way to go.

00:03:35.930 --> 00:03:37.040
We have momentum with us.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:39.570
There are Republicans
and Democrats alike

00:03:39.570 --> 00:03:42.820
who are working with
us who are really

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:44.390
championing these reforms.

00:03:44.390 --> 00:03:47.770
And I think really the
underlying motivation often

00:03:47.770 --> 00:03:49.880
comes from the stories
of the people who

00:03:49.880 --> 00:03:52.526
are directly impacted who
are key partners in our work.

00:03:52.526 --> 00:03:56.275
And one of them is here with
us today to share his story.

00:03:56.275 --> 00:03:59.070
