Sorry, Jody.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:21.340
But I'm really happy to be
here, and most importantly,

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:25.450
because I was able to visit
with some individuals yesterday

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:28.410
at San Quentin Prison.

00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:30.540
Walking in for me
personally is always

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:34.260
a challenge when I go
into a secure facility

00:05:34.260 --> 00:05:37.600
because to be quite honest with
you, up until 13 years ago,

00:05:37.600 --> 00:05:41.020
I grew up in secure facilities
throughout the state

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:42.110
of Illinois.

00:05:42.110 --> 00:05:44.240
I was convicted at
a very early age--

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:47.520
at the age of 13 years old--
for first degree murder.

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:48.220
I was guilty.

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:49.040
I was responsible.

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:50.990
And I plead guilty.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:54.020
But at that age, what was
mostly unspoken in my life

00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:56.650
was the fact that not
only was I someone

00:05:56.650 --> 00:06:01.240
who had a very unfortunate
track record of repeated arrests

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:03.480
and convictions, but I
was also a child that

00:06:03.480 --> 00:06:06.417
had endured some very
horrific things early on which

00:06:06.417 --> 00:06:09.000
sort of manifested itself in a
very devastating way-- in a way

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.800
which I had landed
in the justice system

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:16.060
with a 25-year sentence of
the age of 13 years old.

00:06:16.060 --> 00:06:20.610
I was fortunate to have a
public defender, [INAUDIBLE] who

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:24.020
recognized my youthfulness first
and foremost-- something that

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:30.370
at that time in the late 1980s,
unfortunately, was not being

00:06:30.370 --> 00:06:32.630
recognized for many children.

00:06:32.630 --> 00:06:35.500
When I stood in that
sally port waiting

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.950
to be transferred over
to the Cook County Court,

00:06:37.950 --> 00:06:38.790
I wasn't alone.

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:41.622
There were many other kids that
were shackled alongside me.

00:06:41.622 --> 00:06:44.080
And I remember being transferred
over into the adult court.

00:06:44.080 --> 00:06:48.640
And I remember when we
walked into the tunnel,

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:51.160
we went into the tunnel
of the Cook County Court.

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:54.900
We went up a very grim
and dark elevator.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:57.430
When we got to the
courthouse level,

00:06:57.430 --> 00:06:59.590
we had to walk
past some bullpens.

00:06:59.590 --> 00:07:01.720
And when we went
past the bullpens,

00:07:01.720 --> 00:07:04.120
they were populated with
a bunch of individuals

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:06.220
who were awaiting trial
who had just been arrested

00:07:06.220 --> 00:07:08.480
or being processed
into their division.

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:11.140
And I remember hearing a
lot of the guys yelling out

00:07:11.140 --> 00:07:15.990
of the cracks in the bars
saying, man, that's messed up.

00:07:15.990 --> 00:07:18.820
And they're saying all these
things-- a little profanity,

00:07:18.820 --> 00:07:22.630
but expressing something that it
took me a while to catch on to.

00:07:22.630 --> 00:07:26.590
But what they were expressing
was their anger and how upset

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:28.870
they were that us,
that little children,

00:07:28.870 --> 00:07:31.240
were being taken into
the same courtrooms,

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:33.340
being faced with the
same consequences,

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:35.450
that they were being faced with.

00:07:35.450 --> 00:07:39.470
And I think that looking
at that in retrospect,

00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:44.380
it made me question our own
way of dealing with kids today.

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:46.710
And if these individuals
who are deemed

00:07:46.710 --> 00:07:48.460
as the worst of the
worst in our society--

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:52.270
if they can have the humanity
and compassion to recognize

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:54.110
that these were
just children, why

00:07:54.110 --> 00:07:57.030
can't others individuals
who are involved in creating

00:07:57.030 --> 00:08:01.471
these systems and designed the
treatment programs very early

00:08:01.471 --> 00:08:03.970
on-- why can't they recognize
the needs of our children, who

00:08:03.970 --> 00:08:06.180
for most part have
been failed by so many?

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:09.040
And so not to make an
excuse for my past mistakes,

00:08:09.040 --> 00:08:11.710
but I would simply say
that I was not alone.

00:08:11.710 --> 00:08:12.820
There were many of us.

00:08:12.820 --> 00:08:15.950
We came from different
communities and cities

00:08:15.950 --> 00:08:16.930
across the state.

00:08:16.930 --> 00:08:19.190
But for the most part, we
had some things in common.

00:08:19.190 --> 00:08:23.570
And those things were
trauma, first and foremost.

00:08:23.570 --> 00:08:26.830
Second of all, many of us
were living in households

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:29.530
that were very hostile, had
struggled mental illness,

00:08:29.530 --> 00:08:30.220
substance abuse.

00:08:30.220 --> 00:08:32.400
We lived in poor
[INAUDIBLE] communities.

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:34.650
We lived in environments
that were very toxic,

00:08:34.650 --> 00:08:37.015
not nurturing,
and unfortunately,

00:08:37.015 --> 00:08:42.220
were producing some very
poor decisions on our behalf.

00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:45.052
As early as six years old, I
was placed in a foster care.

00:08:45.052 --> 00:08:46.760
And in fact, that was
the very first time

00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:50.050
I was placed in a police
car for that transport.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:52.470
And when I got out of
the foster care system

00:08:52.470 --> 00:08:54.120
two and a half years
later, I went back

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:55.744
to the same poor
[INAUDIBLE] community,

00:08:55.744 --> 00:08:58.007
went back to the same
poverty, the same struggle--

00:08:58.007 --> 00:08:59.590
the mental illness
and substance abuse

00:08:59.590 --> 00:09:01.260
that took place
to my home-- and I

00:09:01.260 --> 00:09:02.680
wasn't able to rise above that.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:06.680
And I wasn't able to
escape the negative impacts

00:09:06.680 --> 00:09:08.400
of those traumas very early on.

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:11.110
And so I gravitated
towards a gang life.

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:13.540
And what I think that
is often, I guess,

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:16.474
unspoken, as well, is that
these individuals, these kids--

00:09:16.474 --> 00:09:18.140
although they made
these poor decisions,

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:21.000
in their heart of hearts,
they're really not bad kids.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.110
And that's why our model
as a national network,

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:26.150
the Incarcerated Children's
Action Network, is no child

00:09:26.150 --> 00:09:27.200
is born bad.

00:09:27.200 --> 00:09:29.450
It's not a coincidence that
the majority of these kids

00:09:29.450 --> 00:09:31.582
are coming from these
type of upbringings.

00:09:31.582 --> 00:09:33.040
And so the age of
13 years old when

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:35.112
I was faced with 20
to 60 years in prison,

00:09:35.112 --> 00:09:36.820
I had a strong advocate,
as I mentioned--

00:09:36.820 --> 00:09:39.090
my public defender-- who
fought very hard for me.

00:09:39.090 --> 00:09:42.520
And she convinced the judge
to give me a 25-year sentence.

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:44.490
And I know that
may sound extreme.

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:46.457
But under the old law,
that meant day-for-day,

00:09:46.457 --> 00:09:48.040
meaning for every
good day you served,

00:09:48.040 --> 00:09:49.950
I would have a day
taken off my time.

00:09:49.950 --> 00:09:51.750
I would have an
opportunity in my mid 20s

00:09:51.750 --> 00:09:54.367
to be able to come out, recreate
myself, and start a new life.

00:09:54.367 --> 00:09:56.700
And unfortunately, individuals
that I met with yesterday

00:09:56.700 --> 00:10:00.030
in San Quentin don't
have that option.

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:02.790
The individuals in San Quentin,
although they were in their 30s

00:10:02.790 --> 00:10:07.210
and 40s, and one gentleman had
been in prison for 40 years

00:10:07.210 --> 00:10:09.680
since he was a
teenager-- because

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:11.300
of the seriousness
of his offense,

00:10:11.300 --> 00:10:14.390
he has been told repeatedly by
a parole board he would never

00:10:14.390 --> 00:10:17.320
be free despite his
positive change,

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:19.930
despite the fact that he's
involved himself in programs,

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:22.750
has helped to build a
sweat lodge on campus,

00:10:22.750 --> 00:10:24.370
one of the first
ones in the state;

00:10:24.370 --> 00:10:27.890
has helped to mentor young
kids coming into prisons,

00:10:27.890 --> 00:10:31.485
at-risk youth who have been
brought into the prison walls

00:10:31.485 --> 00:10:33.610
to learn from those who
have made horrible mistakes

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:35.670
but who want to help
children make better ones

00:10:35.670 --> 00:10:36.810
in their lives.

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:38.960
And despite all this
positive change,

00:10:38.960 --> 00:10:42.220
despite what's undeniable within
himself, and unfortunately,

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:44.110
within many of
those around him, he

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:48.130
would never be free unless we
bring about the type of reforms

00:10:48.130 --> 00:10:49.302
that we're fighting for.

00:10:49.302 --> 00:10:51.760
And that's why I'm very happy
to be a part of the campaign.

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:55.540
I'm very happy to be able to
lend my voice as someone who's

00:10:55.540 --> 00:10:58.320
not exceptional, who's not
the exception to the rule,

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:01.410
but as someone
whose life is really

00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:04.300
indicative of every child's
capacity for positive change--

00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:08.200
that none of us are beyond
redemption, beyond repair--

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:11.230
and that at the very
young age of 18 years old,

00:11:11.230 --> 00:11:13.530
after having been in
prison for five years,

00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:17.250
that I was able to reach a
point of maturity and awareness

00:11:17.250 --> 00:11:19.240
that made me reflect
upon my life.

00:11:19.240 --> 00:11:21.440
It made me desire something
bigger and better.

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.720
It made me recognize that many
of the things that I had done

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:27.020
up until that point were not
really reflective of who I

00:11:27.020 --> 00:11:29.210
really was inside,
but that, in fact, I

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:31.080
was a product of
my environment--

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:34.180
that, in fact, I was working
out of those untreated

00:11:34.180 --> 00:11:36.900
traumas, those emotion
deprivations that made me

00:11:36.900 --> 00:11:38.550
susceptible to
peer pressure, made

00:11:38.550 --> 00:11:42.380
me more susceptible to do things
that are outside my nature.

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:46.010
But at the age of a growing
sense of maturity and remorse,

00:11:46.010 --> 00:11:48.040
I decided to take
control of my life.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:50.410
I decided to get myself
involved in the school,

00:11:50.410 --> 00:11:52.620
to leave the gang that
I was associated with,

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:54.070
to get my life on track.

00:11:54.070 --> 00:11:57.270
And I had sort of envisioned
a parallel universe.

00:11:57.270 --> 00:12:00.170
I had envisioned my life--
as it was, obviously,

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:02.710
within the prison walls--
but how it would also look

00:12:02.710 --> 00:12:04.650
had I never been incarcerated.

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:07.240
And I told myself
at 17, 18 years old,

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.420
I would have finished
high school at that point.

00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:11.920
And because of that
mindset, I said,

00:12:11.920 --> 00:12:13.045
well, I need to get my GED.

00:12:13.045 --> 00:12:14.840
And I knocked it out right away.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:16.989
And I said what
would I be at 21?

00:12:16.989 --> 00:12:18.780
And I said I'll have
my associate's degree.

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:21.410
So I pursued my
associate's degree.

00:12:21.410 --> 00:12:23.510
Where would I be at 23, 24?

00:12:23.510 --> 00:12:25.906
I would probably have
my bachelor's by then.

00:12:25.906 --> 00:12:27.280
And if I could
have, I would have

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:29.779
worked for my master's, but I
had to wait until years later.

00:12:29.779 --> 00:12:32.420
But I was able to enroll
myself into a bachelor's degree

00:12:32.420 --> 00:12:34.960
program and get a bachelor's
degree in social science

00:12:34.960 --> 00:12:37.740
with a 4.0 GPA, was inducted
into the Franklin Honor

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:39.620
Society for Outstanding
Scholarship,

00:12:39.620 --> 00:12:41.390
and was really
excelling academically,

00:12:41.390 --> 00:12:43.424
and was really
taking on this belief

00:12:43.424 --> 00:12:45.840
that I could do something
better in my life upon release--

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.810
a release date that
was within years away

00:12:48.810 --> 00:12:52.290
and which enabled me to have
a greater hope for a better

00:12:52.290 --> 00:12:53.180
future.

00:12:53.180 --> 00:12:55.319
Unfortunately, many people
don't have the light

00:12:55.319 --> 00:12:56.360
at the end of the tunnel.

00:12:56.360 --> 00:12:58.568
Many individuals like some
of the kids that I grew up

00:12:58.568 --> 00:13:00.602
with in the system
are still there today.

00:13:00.602 --> 00:13:03.060
And because of that, it is not
that I carry some survivor's

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:05.720
guilt, but I certainly
carry a responsibility--

00:13:05.720 --> 00:13:07.800
a sense of responsibility
that tells me

00:13:07.800 --> 00:13:10.140
that I should not
forget who they are

00:13:10.140 --> 00:13:12.940
and that I should amplify their
messages and their stories;

00:13:12.940 --> 00:13:15.940
that I should make known to
the world that not just myself,

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:17.540
but many others
within the system

00:13:17.540 --> 00:13:19.960
have such great potentials,
for many unfortunately

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:21.750
their potential is
being wasted away.

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:24.370
That such dreams and
hopes and even better

00:13:24.370 --> 00:13:26.880
hopes and for our
communities are simply

00:13:26.880 --> 00:13:29.770
languishing away there
behind prison walls

00:13:29.770 --> 00:13:35.090
and costing millions of
tax dollars, unnecessarily.

00:13:35.090 --> 00:13:36.677
And so when we
talk about reform,

00:13:36.677 --> 00:13:38.635
we're talking about not
just a legal obligation

00:13:38.635 --> 00:13:42.690
and a moral obligation, but also
the most commonsense obligation

00:13:42.690 --> 00:13:44.742
that we have to ourselves
and to our community,

00:13:44.742 --> 00:13:46.200
and not only that,
but to recognize

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:48.440
the needs of those
who have been harmed--

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.550
not just those who
have entered the system

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:53.200
and have experienced
traumas and made

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:55.070
poor decisions,
but also those who

00:13:55.070 --> 00:13:58.170
have been impacted by violence.

00:13:58.170 --> 00:14:00.592
A great part of our work
as a national network

00:14:00.592 --> 00:14:02.300
is to address the
needs of the community.

00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:06.340
Many of us work in a capacity
as substance abuse counselors.

00:14:06.340 --> 00:14:09.500
Many of us work in a capacity
as youth development program

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:10.460
coordinators.

00:14:10.460 --> 00:14:12.730
Many of us work in a
capacity of employing

00:14:12.730 --> 00:14:14.320
formerly incarcerated folks.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:16.500
And so this is the work
that we do in our own lives.

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:19.280
And I often say the Incarcerated
Children's Advocacy Network,

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:21.696
which is a national network
reforming incarcerated youth--

00:14:21.696 --> 00:14:24.310
when they came to us,
they were already leaders.

00:14:24.310 --> 00:14:26.930
But had you met them
in a public space

00:14:26.930 --> 00:14:28.389
or at a conference
or an event, you

00:14:28.389 --> 00:14:30.263
would have never known
that as children, they

00:14:30.263 --> 00:14:32.300
were all convicted of
homicide-related offenses.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:34.200
You would have never
known that many of them

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:35.800
were once sentenced to life
without the possibility

00:14:35.800 --> 00:14:36.299
of parole.

00:14:36.299 --> 00:14:41.030
But because the pardons
and exonerations

00:14:41.030 --> 00:14:44.410
and other legal interventions,
that they're now

00:14:44.410 --> 00:14:47.670
able to be out to live a normal
life and to show the world

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:51.400
that they, too, were able to
recreate and start a new life.

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:53.060
And so that is our
hope for many others

00:14:53.060 --> 00:14:54.260
who are serving that time.

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:57.250
We also hope that
individuals who are out

00:14:57.250 --> 00:14:58.820
and who are formerly
incarcerated

00:14:58.820 --> 00:15:00.111
will continue to work together.

00:15:00.111 --> 00:15:00.980
So we often convene.

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:02.410
We convene annually.

00:15:02.410 --> 00:15:03.570
We train together.

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:04.570
We work with each other.

00:15:04.570 --> 00:15:07.310
We're supportive of one another.

00:15:07.310 --> 00:15:09.560
We also come together
for workshops

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:11.540
that help us hone our
skills as advocates

00:15:11.540 --> 00:15:16.080
to be better advocates for those
who we often in so many ways

00:15:16.080 --> 00:15:18.250
try to represent.

00:15:18.250 --> 00:15:20.990
And so that is really
a big purpose of ICAN.

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:24.000
But another big purpose
of our national network

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.550
is really to keep
those who are currently

00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:28.990
incarcerated informed,
and then not only that,

00:15:28.990 --> 00:15:31.940
but also to help them understand
that they're not forgotten.

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:34.210
I understand how it
feels to be incarcerated.

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:38.900
I understand in so many
ways the sad reality,

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:42.050
the existential nightmare of
being incarcerated and feeling

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:44.500
forgotten by society.

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:48.270
And it's so easy
for many people not

00:15:48.270 --> 00:15:52.060
to think of those who are
in prison since childhood.

00:15:52.060 --> 00:15:54.560
And in fact, many family
and friends often move on.

00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:57.330
But because of their big hearts
and the willingness of those

00:15:57.330 --> 00:16:00.105
who are on the front lines
of reform and the desire

00:16:00.105 --> 00:16:04.560
and passion they have to help
see their release and life be

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:07.290
recreated, they've been
able to have something

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:10.190
to hold onto-- a hope to believe
in, something to look forward

00:16:10.190 --> 00:16:13.320
to, an incentive
towards positive change.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:15.110
And a sense of that
in so many ways

00:16:15.110 --> 00:16:16.770
has helped even
within the system

00:16:16.770 --> 00:16:19.629
in terms of the prison stability
and preventing violence.

00:16:19.629 --> 00:16:21.670
And oftentimes, these are
the conflict mediators.

00:16:21.670 --> 00:16:24.010
Oftentimes, they are running
sort of justice programs

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:25.280
within the facilities.

00:16:25.280 --> 00:16:26.170
They're the trustees.

00:16:26.170 --> 00:16:28.660
They're the ones who are
entrusted with yesterday,

00:16:28.660 --> 00:16:33.020
the place we went was
a building that was

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:35.056
unattended for the most part.

00:16:35.056 --> 00:16:36.430
But yet these are
all individuals

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:38.138
who are deemed as the
worst of the worst.

00:16:38.138 --> 00:16:40.770
But yet there was not a single
guard within that facility.

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.230
And they're running their
own programs, programs

00:16:43.230 --> 00:16:46.280
that have affected upon their
own sense of masculinity,

00:16:46.280 --> 00:16:49.910
their own sense of how
to overcome their trauma,

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:53.550
who they are today,
what does empathy mean.

00:16:53.550 --> 00:16:56.470
These are questions
that we hardly even

00:16:56.470 --> 00:16:58.140
entertain in free society.

00:16:58.140 --> 00:17:00.240
But yet they're digging
deep within themselves

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:03.820
to discover who they really are,
to discover their own humanity,

00:17:03.820 --> 00:17:05.650
to find ways-- and
innovative ways,

00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:07.940
in fact-- to give back
to their communities,

00:17:07.940 --> 00:17:11.569
to have cancer awareness
marches within the facility,

00:17:11.569 --> 00:17:13.700
to have events in
which they were

00:17:13.700 --> 00:17:15.760
able to create origami
hearts for kids who

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:19.589
are in hospitals, to have events
where they're able to create

00:17:19.589 --> 00:17:22.910
food can drives and food
drives to give to the homeless.

00:17:22.910 --> 00:17:26.010
And all this is taking place
within the prison walls.

00:17:26.010 --> 00:17:28.319
And yet when they
had to organize

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:30.400
an event, a
fundraising event, they

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:32.870
came to find that the
inmates and the families

00:17:32.870 --> 00:17:34.480
gave more than the community.

00:17:34.480 --> 00:17:35.980
And that just goes
to show the level

00:17:35.980 --> 00:17:39.274
of desire they have to live
out that eternal apology,

00:17:39.274 --> 00:17:41.440
to give back to the
communities, to sort of live out

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:43.390
the sort of penances
that we all carry

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:45.720
and a desire to make
amends with society.

00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:50.400
And so I hope that all of
you at Google in some ways

00:17:50.400 --> 00:17:54.880
recognize the value of their
human potential, the value

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:56.210
of what they had to offer.

00:17:56.210 --> 00:17:58.293
And with that, I want to
turn it back over to Jody

00:17:58.293 --> 00:18:01.150
and give her an opportunity to
share about some possible ways

00:18:01.150 --> 00:18:02.066
in which you can help.

00:18:02.066 --> 00:18:03.926
Thank you.

00:18:03.926 --> 00:18:06.094
[APPLAUSE]

00:18:06.094 --> 00:18:07.510
